#: ../../../building/index.rst:4
msgid "Building from source"
msgstr "從來源碼建置"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:12
msgid ""
"If you are only trying to install NumPy, we recommend using binaries - see "
"`Installation <https://numpy.org/install>`__ for details on that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:15
msgid ""
"Building NumPy from source requires setting up system-level dependencies "
"(compilers, BLAS/LAPACK libraries, etc.) first, and then invoking a build. "
"The build may be done in order to install NumPy for local usage, develop "
"NumPy itself, or build redistributable binary packages. And it may be "
"desired to customize aspects of how the build is done. This guide will cover "
"all these aspects. In addition, it provides background information on how "
"the NumPy build works, and links to up-to-date guides for generic Python "
"build & packaging documentation that is relevant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:27
msgid "System-level dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:29
msgid ""
"NumPy uses compiled code for speed, which means you need compilers and some "
"other system-level (i.e, non-Python / non-PyPI) dependencies to build it on "
"your system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:35
msgid ""
"If you are using Conda, you can skip the steps in this section - with the "
"exception of installing compilers for Windows or the Apple Developer Tools "
"for macOS. All other dependencies will be installed automatically by the "
"``mamba env create -f environment.yml`` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:45
msgid "If you want to use the system Python and ``pip``, you will need:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:47
msgid "C and C++ compilers (typically GCC)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:49
msgid ""
"Python header files (typically a package named ``python3-dev`` or ``python3-"
"devel``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:52
msgid ""
"BLAS and LAPACK libraries. `OpenBLAS <https://github.com/OpenMathLib/"
"OpenBLAS/>`__ is the NumPy default; other variants include Apple Accelerate, "
"`MKL <https://software.intel.com/en-us/intel-mkl>`__, `ATLAS <https://math-"
"atlas.sourceforge.net/>`__ and `Netlib <https://www.netlib.org/lapack/index."
"html>`__ (or \"Reference\") BLAS and LAPACK."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:59
msgid "``pkg-config`` for dependency detection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:61
msgid ""
"A Fortran compiler is needed only for running the ``f2py`` tests. The "
"instructions below include a Fortran compiler, however you can safely leave "
"it out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Debian/Ubuntu Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:69 ../../../building/index.rst:83
#: ../../../building/index.rst:97 ../../../building/index.rst:111
msgid "To install NumPy build requirements, you can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:71
msgid ""
"sudo apt install -y gcc g++ gfortran libopenblas-dev liblapack-dev pkg-"
"config python3-pip python3-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:73 ../../../building/index.rst:87
#: ../../../building/index.rst:101
msgid "Alternatively, you can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:75
msgid "sudo apt build-dep numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:77 ../../../building/index.rst:91
#: ../../../building/index.rst:105
msgid ""
"This command installs whatever is needed to build NumPy, with the advantage "
"that new dependencies or updates to required versions are handled by the "
"package managers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Fedora"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:85
msgid ""
"sudo dnf install gcc-gfortran python3-devel openblas-devel lapack-devel "
"pkgconfig"
msgstr ""
"sudo dnf install gcc-gfortran python3-devel openblas-devel lapack-devel "
"pkgconfig"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:89
msgid "sudo dnf builddep numpy"
msgstr "sudo dnf builddep numpy"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "CentOS/RHEL"
msgstr "CentOS/RHEL"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:99
msgid ""
"sudo yum install gcc-gfortran python3-devel openblas-devel lapack-devel "
"pkgconfig"
msgstr ""
"sudo yum install gcc-gfortran python3-devel openblas-devel lapack-devel "
"pkgconfig"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:103
msgid "sudo yum-builddep numpy"
msgstr "sudo yum-builddep numpy"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Arch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:113
msgid "sudo pacman -S gcc-fortran openblas pkgconf"
msgstr "sudo pacman -S gcc-fortran openblas pkgconf"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "macOS"
msgstr "macOS"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:118
msgid ""
"Install Apple Developer Tools. An easy way to do this is to `open a terminal "
"window <https://blog.teamtreehouse.com/introduction-to-the-mac-os-x-command-"
"line>`_, enter the command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:122
msgid "xcode-select --install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:124
msgid ""
"and follow the prompts. Apple Developer Tools includes Git, the Clang C/C++ "
"compilers, and other development utilities that may be required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:127
msgid ""
"Do *not* use the macOS system Python. Instead, install Python with `the "
"python.org installer <https://www.python.org/downloads/>`__ or with a "
"package manager like Homebrew, MacPorts or Fink."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:131
msgid ""
"On macOS >=13.3, the easiest build option is to use Accelerate, which is "
"already installed and will be automatically used by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:134
msgid ""
"On older macOS versions you need a different BLAS library, most likely "
"OpenBLAS, plus pkg-config to detect OpenBLAS. These are easiest to install "
"with `Homebrew <https://brew.sh/>`__::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:138
msgid "brew install openblas pkg-config gfortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:143
msgid ""
"Compared to macOS and Linux, building NumPy on Windows is a little more "
"difficult, due to the need to set up compilers. First, install Microsoft "
"Visual Studio - the 2019 Community Edition or any newer version will work "
"(see the `Visual Studio download site <https://visualstudio.microsoft.com/"
"downloads/>`__). This is needed to ensure you have the Windows Universal C "
"Runtime. The recommended version of the UCRT is >= 10.0.22621.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:151
msgid ""
"The MSVC installer does not put the compilers on the system path, and the "
"install location may change. To query the install location, MSVC comes with "
"a ``vswhere.exe`` command-line utility. And to make the C/C++ compilers "
"available inside the shell you are using, you need to run a ``.bat`` file "
"for the correct bitness and architecture (e.g., for 64-bit Intel CPUs, use "
"``vcvars64.bat``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:158 ../../../building/index.rst:200
msgid ""
"For detailed guidance, see `Use the Microsoft C++ toolset from the command "
"line <https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/building-on-the-command-"
"line?view=msvc-170>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:161 ../../../building/index.rst:203
msgid ""
"If you don't need ``f2py``, MSVC alone is sufficient. For Fortran compiler "
"setup (needed for ``f2py``), see :ref:`F2PY and Windows <f2py-windows>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:166 ../../../building/index.rst:208
msgid ""
"Compilers should be on the system path (i.e., the ``PATH`` environment "
"variable should contain the directory in which the compiler executables can "
"be found) in order to be found, with the exception of MSVC which will be "
"found automatically if and only if there are no other compilers on the "
"``PATH``. You can use any shell (e.g., Powershell, ``cmd`` or Git Bash) to "
"invoke a build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:175
msgid ""
"When using a conda environment it is possible that the environment creation "
"will not work due to an outdated Fortran compiler. If that happens, remove "
"the ``compilers`` entry from ``environment.yml`` and try again. The Fortran "
"compiler should be installed as described in the :ref:`F2PY Windows "
"documentation <f2py-windows>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Windows on ARM64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:184
msgid ""
"In Windows on ARM64, the compiler options available for building NumPy are "
"limited. GCC and gfortran are not yet supported. Currently, the NumPy build "
"for Windows on ARM64 is supported with MSVC and LLVM toolchains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:188
msgid ""
"First, install Microsoft Visual Studio - the 2022 Community Edition will "
"work (see the `Visual Studio download site <https://visualstudio.microsoft."
"com/downloads/>`__). Ensure that you have installed necessary Visual Studio "
"components for building NumPy on WoA from `here <https://gist.github.com/"
"Mugundanmcw/c3bb93018d5da9311fb2b222f205ba19>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:193
msgid ""
"The MSVC installer does not put the compilers on the system path, and the "
"install location may change. To query the install location, MSVC comes with "
"a ``vswhere.exe`` command-line utility. And to make the C/C++ compilers "
"available inside the shell you are using, you need to run a ``.bat`` file "
"for the correct bitness and architecture (e.g., for ARM64-based CPUs, use "
"``vcvarsarm64.bat``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:217
msgid ""
"Currently, Conda environment is not yet supported officially on `Windows on "
"ARM64 <https://github.com/conda-forge/conda-forge.github.io/issues/1940>`__. "
"The present approach uses virtualenv for building NumPy from source on "
"Windows on ARM64."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:223
msgid "Building NumPy from source"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:225
msgid ""
"If you want to only install NumPy from source once and not do any "
"development work, then the recommended way to build and install is to use "
"``pip``. Otherwise, conda is recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:231
msgid ""
"If you don't have a conda installation yet, we recommend using Miniforge_; "
"any conda flavor will work though."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:235
msgid "Building from source to use NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Conda env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:242
msgid ""
"If you are using a conda environment, ``pip`` is still the tool you use to "
"invoke a from-source build of NumPy. It is important to always use the ``--"
"no-build-isolation`` flag to the ``pip install`` command, to avoid building "
"against a ``numpy`` wheel from PyPI. In order for that to work you must "
"first install the remaining build dependencies into the conda environment::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:249
msgid ""
"# Either install all NumPy dev dependencies into a fresh conda environment\n"
"mamba env create -f environment.yml\n"
"\n"
"# Or, install only the required build dependencies\n"
"mamba install python numpy cython compilers openblas meson-python pkg-"
"config\n"
"\n"
"# To build the latest stable release:\n"
"pip install numpy --no-build-isolation --no-binary numpy\n"
"\n"
"# To build a development version, you need a local clone of the NumPy git "
"repository:\n"
"git clone https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git\n"
"cd numpy\n"
"git submodule update --init\n"
"pip install . --no-build-isolation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:266
msgid ""
"On Windows, the AR, LD, and LDFLAGS environment variables may be set, which "
"will cause the pip install command to fail. These variables are only needed "
"for flang and can be safely unset prior to running pip install."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:0
msgid "Virtual env or system Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:275
msgid ""
"# To build the latest stable release:\n"
"pip install numpy --no-binary numpy\n"
"\n"
"# To build a development version, you need a local clone of the NumPy git "
"repository:\n"
"git clone https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git\n"
"cd numpy\n"
"git submodule update --init\n"
"pip install ."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:289
msgid "Building from source for NumPy development"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:291
msgid ""
"If you want to build from source in order to work on NumPy itself, first "
"clone the NumPy repository::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:294
msgid ""
"git clone https://github.com/numpy/numpy.git\n"
"cd numpy\n"
"git submodule update --init"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:298
msgid "Then you want to do the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:300
msgid ""
"Create a dedicated development environment (virtual environment or conda "
"environment),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:302
msgid ""
"Install all needed dependencies (*build*, and also *test*, *doc* and "
"*optional* dependencies),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:304
msgid "Build NumPy with the ``spin`` developer interface."
msgstr "使用 ``spin`` 開發者介面建置 NumPy。"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:306
msgid ""
"Step (3) is always the same, steps (1) and (2) are different between conda "
"and virtual environments:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:314
msgid ""
"To create a ``numpy-dev`` development environment with every required and "
"optional dependency installed, run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:317
msgid ""
"mamba env create -f environment.yml\n"
"mamba activate numpy-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:325
msgid ""
"There are many tools to manage virtual environments, like ``venv``, "
"``virtualenv``/``virtualenvwrapper``, ``pyenv``/``pyenv-virtualenv``, "
"Poetry, PDM, Hatch, and more. Here we use the basic ``venv`` tool that is "
"part of the Python stdlib. You can use any other tool; all we need is an "
"activated Python environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:331
msgid ""
"Create and activate a virtual environment in a new directory named ``venv`` "
"( note that the exact activation command may be different based on your OS "
"and shell - see `\"How venvs work\" <https://docs.python.org/3/library/venv."
"html#how-venvs-work>`__ in the ``venv`` docs)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:343 ../../../building/index.rst:351
msgid ""
"python -m venv venv\n"
"source venv/bin/activate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:359 ../../../building/index.rst:367
msgid ""
"python -m venv venv\n"
".\\venv\\Scripts\\activate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:372
msgid ""
"Building NumPy with BLAS and LAPACK functions requires OpenBLAS library at "
"Runtime. In Windows on ARM64, this can be done by setting up pkg-config for "
"OpenBLAS dependency. The build steps for OpenBLAS for Windows on ARM64 can "
"be found `here <http://www.openmathlib.org/OpenBLAS/docs/install/#windows-on-"
"arm>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:378
msgid "Then install the Python-level dependencies from PyPI with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:380
msgid "python -m pip install -r requirements/build_requirements.txt"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:382
msgid "To build NumPy in an activated development environment, run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:384
msgid "spin build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:386
msgid ""
"This will install NumPy inside the repository (by default in a ``build-"
"install`` directory). You can then run tests (``spin test``), drop into "
"IPython (``spin ipython``), or take other development steps like build the "
"html documentation or running benchmarks. The ``spin`` interface is self-"
"documenting, so please see ``spin --help`` and ``spin <subcommand> --help`` "
"for detailed guidance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:395
msgid ""
"In an activated conda environment on Windows, the AR, LD, and LDFLAGS "
"environment variables may be set, which will cause the build to fail. These "
"variables are only needed for flang and can be safely unset for build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:402
msgid "IDE support & editable installs"
msgstr "IDE 支援與可編輯安裝"

#: ../../../building/index.rst:404
msgid ""
"While the ``spin`` interface is our recommended way of working on NumPy, it "
"has one limitation: because of the custom install location, NumPy installed "
"using ``spin`` will not be recognized automatically within an IDE (e.g., for "
"running a script via a \"run\" button, or setting breakpoints visually). "
"This will work better with an *in-place build* (or \"editable install\")."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:411
msgid ""
"Editable installs are supported. It is important to understand that **you "
"may use either an editable install or** ``spin`` **in a given repository "
"clone, but not both**. If you use editable installs, you have to use "
"``pytest`` and other development tools directly instead of using ``spin``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:416
msgid ""
"To use an editable install, ensure you start from a clean repository (run "
"``git clean -xdf`` if you've built with ``spin`` before) and have all "
"dependencies set up correctly as described higher up on this page. Then do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:421
msgid ""
"# Note: the --no-build-isolation is important!\n"
"pip install -e . --no-build-isolation\n"
"\n"
"# To run the tests for, e.g., the `numpy.linalg` module:\n"
"pytest numpy/linalg"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:427
msgid ""
"When making changes to NumPy code, including to compiled code, there is no "
"need to manually rebuild or reinstall. NumPy is automatically rebuilt each "
"time NumPy is imported by the Python interpreter; see the meson-python_ "
"documentation on editable installs for more details on how that works under "
"the hood."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:433
msgid ""
"When you run ``git clean -xdf``, which removes the built extension modules, "
"remember to also uninstall NumPy with ``pip uninstall numpy``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../building/index.rst:439
msgid ""
"Note that editable installs are fundamentally incomplete installs. Their "
"only guarantee is that ``import numpy`` works - so they are suitable for "
"working on NumPy itself, and for working on pure Python packages that depend "
"on NumPy. Headers, entrypoints, and other such things may not be available "
"from an editable install."
msgstr ""

